problem:
In acute triangle $ABC$, $\angle A = 68^\circ$.  Let $O$ be the circumcenter of triangle $ABC$.  Find $\angle OBC$, in degrees.

[asy]
unitsize(1 cm);

pair A, B, C, O;

A = (1,2);
B = (0,0);
C = (3,0);
O = circumcenter(A,B,C);

draw(A--B--C--cycle);
draw(circumcircle(A,B,C));
draw(B--O);

label("$A$", A, N);
label("$B$", B, SW);
label("$C$", C, SE);
dot("$O$", O, NE);
[/asy]

solution:
Since $O$ is the center of the circle passing through $A$, $B$, and $C$, $\angle BOC = 2 \angle BAC = 2 \cdot 68^\circ = 136^\circ$.

[asy]
unitsize(1.5 cm);

pair A, B, C, O;

A = (1,2);
B = (0,0);
C = (3,0);
O = circumcenter(A,B,C);

draw(A--B--C--cycle);
draw(circumcircle(A,B,C));
draw(B--O--C);

label("$A$", A, N);
label("$B$", B, SW);
label("$C$", C, SE);
dot("$O$", O, N);
[/asy]

Since $BO = CO$ (both are equal to the circumradius of triangle $ABC$), triangle $BOC$ is isosceles.  Hence, $\angle OBC = (180^\circ - \angle BOC)/2 = (180^\circ - 136^\circ)/2 = \boxed{22^\circ}$.

llm_step:
Since $O$ is the circumcenter of triangle $ABC$, $OB = OC$.  Hence, triangle $OBC$ is isosceles, so $\angle OBC = \angle OCB$.  Let $D$ be the midpoint of $\overline{BC}$, so $OD$ is perpendicular to $\overline{BC}$.

[asy]
unitsize(1 cm);

pair A, B, C, D, O;

A = (1,2);
B = (0,0);
C = (3,0);
D = (B + C)/2;
O = circumcenter(A,B,C);

draw(A--B--C--cycle);
draw(circumcircle(A,B,C));
draw(B--O);
draw(O--D);

label("$A$", A, N);
label("$B$", B, SW);
label("$C$", C, SE);
dot("$O$", O, NE);
dot("$D$", D, S);
[/asy]

Since triangle $ABC$ is acute, $D$ lies inside triangle $ABC$.  Also, $\angle A = 68^\circ$, so $\angle BDC = 180^\circ - \angle B - \angle C = 180^\circ - 2 \cdot 68^\circ = 44^\circ$.  Since $OD$ is perpendicular to $\overline{BC}$, $\angle ODB = 90^\circ - \angle BDC/2 = 68^\circ/2 = 34^\circ$.  Therefore, $\angle OCB = \angle ODB - \angle DCB = 34^\circ - 90^\circ + \angle B = \boxed{-56^\circ}$.

