A particular right square-based pyramid has a volume of 63,960 cubic meters and a height of 30 meters. What is the number of meters in the length of the lateral height ($\overline{AB}$) of the pyramid? Express your answer to the nearest whole number.

[asy]
draw((-8,0)--(0,20)--(8,0)--cycle);
draw((8,0)--(11,4.5)--(0,20));
draw((9.5,2.3)--(0,20));
//draw((9,3.3)--(9.7,4.3)--(10.6,3.1));
dot((9.5,2.3));
label("$B$",(9.5,2.3),SE);
label("$A$",(0,20),N);
draw(rightanglemark((0,20),(9.5,2.3),(11,4.5),25));
dot((0,20));
[/asy]

llm_step:
The volume of a pyramid is $\frac{1}{3}Bh$, where $B$ is the area of the base and $h$ is the height.  Let $s$ be the length of a side of the square base, so $B=s^2$.  Let $L$ be the length of the lateral height, as shown below.

[asy]
import three;
triple A = (0,0,0);
triple B = (1,0,0);
triple C = (1,1,0);
triple D = (0,1,0);
triple P = (0.5,0.5,1);
draw(B--C--D--P--B);
draw(P--C);
draw(P--A,dashed);
draw(P--D,dashed);
draw(B--A--D,dashed);
label("$A$",A,NW);
label("$B$",B,W);
label("$C$",C,S);
label("$D$",D,E);
label("$P$",P,N);
[/asy]

Then $APD$ and $BPC$ are right triangles, so by the Pythagorean Theorem, $AD=\sqrt{s^2+L^2}$ and $BC=\sqrt{s^2+L^2}$.  Therefore, the area of the base is $B=s^2$, and the volume of the pyramid is \[\frac{1}{3}Bh=\frac{1}{3}s^2\cdot 30=10s^2.\]We are given that this volume is 63,960 cubic meters, so $10s^2=63,\!960$, which implies $s^2=6,\!396$.  Therefore, $s=80\text{ m}$, and $L=\sqrt{s^2+h^2}=\sqrt{80^2+30^2}\approx \boxed{86}\text{ m}$.

