pair M, Q, Qp;
M = (2,5);
Q = (2,7);
Qp = (-1,2);
draw(M--Q--Qp--cycle);
draw(rightanglemark(M,Q,Qp,10));
label("$M$", M, SW);
label("$Q$", Q, N);
label("$Q'$", Qp, W);
[/asy] We can find the coordinates of $Q'$ by reflecting $Q$ across the line $MQ$. Since $MQ$ is vertical, the $y$-coordinate of $Q'$ is the same as the $y$-coordinate of $Q$, and the $x$-coordinate of $Q'$ is twice the $x$-coordinate of $M$ minus the $x$-coordinate of $Q$. Thus, $Q' = (2 \cdot 2 - 2, 7) = (2, 7)$.

Next, we reflect $Q'$ across the line $x = 1$. Since $Q'$ is to the right of the line $x = 1$, its reflection $Q''$ is to the left of the line. The distance between $Q'$ and $x = 1$ is $1$, so the distance between $Q''$ and $x = 1$ is also $1$. Thus, the $x$-coordinate of $Q''$ is $1 - (2 - 1) = 0$, and the $y$-coordinate of $Q''$ is the same as the $y$-coordinate of $Q'$, namely $7$. Therefore, $Q'' = \boxed{(0, 7)}$.

