Let $A,$ $B,$ and $C$ be three noncollinear points on the circle.  Without loss of generality, we can assume that $\angle ABC$ is acute.  Then $\angle BAC$ and $\angle BCA$ are obtuse.

[asy]
unitsize(2 cm);

pair A, B, C, O;

O = (0,0);
A = dir(60);
B = dir(180);
C = dir(300);

draw(Circle(O,1));
draw(A--B--C--cycle);

label("$A$", A, N);
label("$B$", B, W);
label("$C$", C, S);
[/asy]

Let $O$ be the center of the circle.  Then $OA = OB = OC = 1,$ so triangle $ABC$ is isosceles.  Furthermore, $\angle BOC = 60^\circ,$ so triangle $BOC$ is equilateral.  Therefore, $BC = 1.$

Let $D$ be the foot of the altitude from $A$ to $BC.$  Then $BD = CD = \frac{1}{2},$ so triangle $ABD$ and triangle $ACD$ are 30-60-90 triangles.  Therefore, $AD = \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2}.$

[asy]
unitsize(2 cm);

pair A, B, C, D, O;

O = (0,0);
A = dir(60);
B = dir(180);
C = dir(300);
D = foot(A,B,C);

draw(Circle(O,1));
draw(A--B--C--cycle);
draw(A--D);

label("$A$", A, N);
label("$B$", B, W);
label("$C$", C, S);
label("$D$", D, SE);
[/asy]

Then the area of triangle $ABC$ is
\[\frac{1}{2} \cdot BC \cdot AD = \frac{1}{2} \cdot 1 \cdot \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} = \boxed{\frac{\sqrt{3}}{4}}.\]

