[asy]
unitsize(1.5 cm);

pair[] A;
int i;

for (i = 0; i <= 6; ++i) {
  A[i] = dir(360*i/7);
  dot(A[i]);
}

draw(A[0]--A[2]--A[4]--cycle);
label("$P$", A[0], N);
label("$Q$", A[2], S);
label("$R$", A[4], N);
[/asy]

Let $z = q/p$ and $w = r/p$.  Then $|z| = |w| = 1$, and
\[\angle PQR = \angle QPR = \arg(w/z).\]Since $|z| = |w| = 1$, we have $z = e^{i\theta}$ and $w = e^{i\phi}$ for some angles $\theta$ and $\phi$.  Then
\[\arg(w/z) = \phi - \theta + 2\pi k\]for some integer $k$.  Therefore, $\angle PQR$ can take on any value of the form $\phi - \theta + 2\pi k$, where $\phi$ and $\theta$ are the arguments of $w$ and $z$, respectively, and $k$ is an integer.  Since there are seven possible values of $z$ and seven possible values of $w$, there are $7 \cdot 7 = 49$ possible values of $\angle PQR$.  (Note that some of these values may be repeated.)  The answer is $\boxed{49}$.

