unitsize(0.4 cm);

pair A, B, C, D;

A = (0,8);
B = (-6,0);
C = (10,0);
D = (A + reflect(B,C)*(A))/2;

draw(A--B--C--cycle);
draw(A--D);

label("$A$", A, N);
label("$B$", B, SW);
label("$C$", C, SE);
label("$D$", D, S);
label("$6$", (A + B)/2, NW);
label("$8$", (B + C)/2, NE);
label("$10$", (A + C)/2, NE);
[/asy]

Then by Stewart's Theorem on triangle $ABD,$
\[AD^2 \cdot BC + BD^2 \cdot AC = AB^2 \cdot DC + CD^2 \cdot AB.\]Since $BD = \frac{3}{2}$ and $DC = \frac{5}{2},$
\[AD^2 \cdot 8 + \frac{9}{4} \cdot 10 = 6^2 \cdot \frac{5}{2} + \frac{25}{4} \cdot 6.\]Solving, we find $AD^2 = \boxed{\frac{289}{16}}.$

