Let us draw a diagram first: [asy]
pair pA, pB, pC, pD;
pD = (0, 0);
pC = pD + dir(0);
pB = pD + dir(180);
pA = pD + dir(100);
draw(pA--pB--pC--pA);
draw(pA--pD);
label("$A$", pA, N);
label("$B$", pB, SW);
label("$C$", pC, SE);
label("$D$", pD, S);
[/asy] As we have isosceles triangles $\triangle ABD$ and $\triangle ACD,$ let us have $\angle ABC = a$ and $\angle ACB = b.$ Then, $\angle BAC =\angle BAD + \angle DAC = a + b.$ Since the three angles must sum to $180^\circ,$ we have that $2(a + b) = 180^\circ,$ so $a + b = 90^\circ.$ Since we know that $a = 50^\circ,$ we see that $b = \angle ACB = \boxed{40^\circ}.$

llm_step:
Let $\angle ADB = \angle ADC = x.$  Then $\angle BDC = 180^\circ - 2x,$ so $\angle BAC = 2x.$

[asy]
unitsize(1 cm);

pair A, B, C, D;

B = (0,0);
C = (2,0);
A = intersectionpoint(arc(B,2,0,180),arc(C,3,0,180));
D = (B + C)/2;

draw(A--B--C--cycle);
draw(A--D);

label("$A$", A, N);
label("$B$", B, SW);
label("$C$", C, SE);
label("$D$", D, S);
[/asy]

Then $\angle ABC = 50^\circ$ and $\angle BAC = 2x,$ so
\[180^\circ - \angle ACB = \angle BAC + \angle ABC = 2x + 50^\circ.\]Since $\angle ADB = x,$ $\angle ADC = x,$ and $\angle BDC = 180^\circ - 2x,$
\[\angle BAC + \angle ACB + \angle BDC = 180^\circ.\]Hence,
\[2x + 50^\circ + \angle ACB + (180^\circ - 2x) = 180^\circ.\]Solving, we find $\angle ACB = \boxed{80^\circ}.$

